I'm visiting from Rhode Island and was so excited to go here after hearing and reading so much about it. And it totally lived up to expectations! The wait wasn't too long..maybe ten minutes. The sandwiches are big! Comes with three good sized pieces and totally worth it. The croque madams were delicious as well. The cookie was good but I'm more into a thick and chewy cookie...theirs is thin and crispy. Eat here! Lived up to all the hype.

I've seen the long, long line outside of Tartine once or twice. And I've always thought to myself, "What on Earth do they serve that's worth waiting for?" Two word answer comin' at ya: morning bun. It doesn't look that awesome at first glance - just an unassuming cinnamon bun looking baked good. The outside is a little dry and crispy, too. But as you work your way inside the swirl, a explosion of orange, cinnamon and vanilla titillates your taste buds. Also worth trying is the brioche bread pudding. Mine came with nectarines and raspberries on top. Delicious and unlike anything I've ever had before. Yes, I ate two breakfasts. So what? Here's another tip for you - go on a weekday right when they open. You won't have to wait at all AND you'll get your goodies fresh as they come. Without spending hours waiting.

The prices! They KILL me. It is SO expensive here JEEBUS CRISTO. It is seriously SO INCREDIBLY overpriced here I wish I cried in dimes. Yet I keep coming back for my once a year fix. Get: the cheese gougere (pronounce it like booger and get laughed at by me BAHAHAHA). Get: the chocolate eclair Get: the croissant (cwa-ssant) Spend loads of money. Ya know, the morning bun? Try this instead: wheat bread toasted with butter with a sprinkling of cinnamon and sugar. MUY BETTER.

I'll make this short and sweet, but if you're interested in reading the deets, feel free to continue reading my extended comments. Skip the... bread pudding. Get the... 1) butter croissant 2) morning bun Take a gamble by ordering... a sandwich. But if you do, you must finish the entire pickled carrot! You'll be disappointed by the... coffee. You'll be lucky to... snag a table. You're better off... ordering to go. Service and attitude? 2 stars... no, really. Would I return? Only for the croissants and morning bun. Would love to try the fruit tort. Want to read more? Go below! Bread pudding: Way too rich and buttery. I missed the awesome bread pudding from m.henry in Chicago, and Tartine's looked relatively close to what I had, but I had been deceived. While the first bite entices you to fork further into the pudding, the longer you eat the it, the more you wish to stop. The one good thing is that the bread pudding has the right amount of sweetness. Pecorino and almond sandwich: If you're craving for a heavy, greasy gourmet grilled cheese sandwich, give this a go. You get your nutty, cheesy, crunchy, and salty. I find it lacking in flavor balance, but hey, this may be your perfect stress food. On another note, they forgot about our croque monsieur even after I asked them about it twice. If I hadn't gone up a third time, it would have been a lost cause. Again, the saving grace of this entire meal was the pastries. Nothing more.

Morning bun is a bit too sweet for my taste, but the banana cream tart is really good! Lemon cream tart looks so cute!

My favorite bakery in San Francisco. I love their morning buns, the seasonal fruit brioche bread pudding, and their assorted confectioneries. The line is worth the wait, but it's also nice to go on an off-day when there is no line. Their 5pm bread is fantastic. Dropping by the cafe window (cash-only, no waiting in line) is also nice. Despite the lines and crowds the staff are always nice and cordial. The only real downside to this place is finding a seat (sometimes actually impossible). I've dropped my food trying to squeeze by so many people.

Try to get in here early because the line will suddenly and without warning be out the door in the blink of an eye. Came here for a quick breakfast and got the Ham and Cheese Croissant. Quality cheese really brings out the flavor of the ham. All of that, wrapped in a blanket of flakey carbs. What's not to like? The Quiche looks like it'd be the most amazing thing in the world, but it's just so-so. Grab a Dark Chocolate Banana Bread Pudding to-go and treat yourself later in the day. Just beware, sometimes it's not ready till later in the day.

Besides the long line, the food looked delicious. The cases are filled. My orange sesame tea bread was delish. Interesting flavor profile.

The most perfect bakery on the planet. I daydream about opening my own bakery, and Tartine is what it'd look like if I did. (But with more cat pictures, let's be honest.) Everything is in the open, and from my place in line, I could see croissants at rest on a workbench. I read in their cookbook that they bake in real-time, which is just amazing. The morning bun and quiche I had were simply perfect. The long line is worth the wait, and it was surprisingly easy to snag a couple of seats.

After reading about this famous bakery, one day I finally gave in and drove there to get some morning buns. The hubs and I got there before they opened and there was a small line already. Ordered our buns and were told to have a seat. They were still finishing them off so it took about 10 mins for the half dozen I ordered to come out piping hot. I couldn't resist taking a few samples on the drive home. Although they were good, it isn't something that I would crave and wait in a line to buy. Their service was great, quick and friendly. Tons of locals hanging out with their morning coffee and newspapers. It is a simple recipe to recreate, although time consuming if I made the dough from scratch

Of course I had to come to Tartine during my SF trip! Joyce and I were a bit worried about the line so we went pretty early, but thankfully the line wasn't too bad. We were sitting at a table with all our food within 30 minutes! The cafe is really small though, so we weren't sure if we would be able to get a table, but the timing worked out just right for us. With so many different pastries and desserts, it was hard to choose what to get, so we decided to get everything!!! Just kidding... we only got six different things :P I also got an Iced Latte, which was good. If you just want coffee/beverages, there is a separate counter you can order at so you don't have to wait in the main line. Croissant -- Light and buttery. Just your normal croissant. Morning Bun -- Fluffy and sweet with a citrus flavour. A bit of a messy eat because of the sugar topping but still pretty good. Brioche Bread Pudding (with Raspberries and Blackberries) -- Very wet/juicy. Would have preferred it to be a little less so, but it was still enjoyable. I liked the berries but would have preferred strawberries. Tres Leches Cake: Sweet coconut milk moistened chiffon, layered with cajeta and crema -- Probably my favourite sweet out of our choices. Light and creamy. Banana Cream Tart (4"): Flaky pastry coated in dark chocolate with caramel, pastry cream, and lightly sweetened cream -- I thought this would be my favourite, except I'm not a fan of dark chocolate. And there was a bit too much of it for me. But the rest of it was good. Croque Monsieur: Open face sandwich with bechamel, gruyere, thyme and pepper. Topped with smoked Niman Ranch ham. -- Pretty good. Pretty much exactly what you expect it to be. Comes with a pickled carrot which is nice. Overall the food was pretty good but not worth all the hype. I wouldn't wait in a long line for it, so I'm glad our line was decently short and moved quickly. But I'm definitely glad I got to try this place out and we had an enjoyable meal.

Visits: 10+ Rating: 4* Service: good We always try to stop by and grab some bread when we're in the area @ the right time. Every time my father in law hears we're heading to SF, he'll call us to request Tartine bread. He loves it that much. Our favorite is the Walnut or Sesame. The best breads are baked in a hearth/brick oven. Hard to beat that thick smokey crust on a brick oven baked bread. Mmm

    7/31/2011Previous review

    I can't stand trendy places and yet find myself lurking closer and closer to the dark side each day I spend in the city. Such was the case when I visited Tartine one Saturday night. I know I know why go at night when you can get their tres tres fresh morning buns in the morn right? Well because I live in NOT SF and sleep in on weekends. Anyway.

    The BF and I ventured here because the devil told us to go. He was chillin' at my house the night before and we kind of hit it off so we went along with his Saturday plans. How tricksy he was though because he convinced us to drive rather than BART to the mission and led us to believe we wouldn't find parking, and only at the moment of shear and utter defeat allowed us a spot. He then led us to a long butt-hole of a long line to a shanty-butt-hole corner bakery called Tartine (though you wouldn't know it lest you had fly eyes). You think he'd lead us to the front at least but alas the devil is a gentleman.

    We were so scared by the menu since it offered devil's food cake--kryptonite for devils. So we stayed away from that and ordered some blinged out treats:

    1 croissant
    1 frangipane tart
    1 chocolate eclair
    1 mex wedding cookie
    (and a surprise to me because the girl got my order wrong:
    1 walnut choco cookie)

    Total bill: $18.

    Can I make any of these myself and want to eat it? Probs not. Will I make it now that I've had it? Probs not.

    The chocolate eclair was the one thing I really wanted since I had it before (I'm a cheater I've been to Tartine times before) along with the croissant (tres tres good) since its a patisserie and croissants are like pastry crack. I sampled other goods just for the heck of it. Frangipane was meh, wedding cookie was overcooked/not melty-in-my-mouthy, and the walnut choco cookie, well, I can definitely make that myself (just gimme some dutch-processed cocoa) so I gave it away to the devil. He burned with joy eating it.

    But the croissant MMMMMMMMM.
    The eclair OHHHYEAHHHH.

    Out of dumb luck my BF just happens to enjoy the caramelized crust of the croissant while I enjoy the succulent inner layers. Can you say match made in not(heaven)?! Anyway, the perfect way to eat a croissant is to peel off layers at a time. Don't be a dummy and bite into it like regular bread. It just tastes better when you tear at it naturally keeping the tender bread fibers in tact.

    The eclair was scrumptious. It is an unpopular option that this yelp review just made popular (just kidding, please trend-setters stay away). It's friggin amazing and vanilla-bean-ified.

    We left the dark side shortly after and ate outside since we found a table open with supreme access to fumes of gas from passing cars/motorcycles and onlooking strangers. The devil tried to make a pass at the waitress cleaning up the tables. What a dummy.

    Till next time, dark side, till next time. I'll get you a $9.50 quiche next time too.

    Tres tres what?

    After reading about this famous bakery, one day I finally gave in and drove there to get some morning buns.  The hubs and I got there before they opened and there was a small line already.  Ordered our buns and were told to have a seat.  They were still finishing them off so it took about 10 mins for the half dozen I ordered to come out piping hot.  I couldn't resist taking a few samples on the drive home.  Although they were good, it isn't something that I would crave and wait in a line to buy.

    Their service was great, quick and friendly.  Tons of locals hanging out with their morning coffee and newspapers.

    It is a simple recipe to recreate, although time consuming if I made the dough from scratch

    1 check-in

    Of course I had to come to Tartine during my SF trip! Joyce and I were a bit worried about the line so we went pretty early, but thankfully the line wasn't too bad. We were sitting at a table with all our food within 30 minutes! The cafe is really small though, so we weren't sure if we would be able to get a table, but the timing worked out just right for us. With so many different pastries and desserts, it was hard to choose what to get, so we decided to get everything!!! Just kidding... we only got six different things :P I also got an Iced Latte, which was good. If you just want coffee/beverages, there is a separate counter you can order at so you don't have to wait in the main line.

    Croissant
    -- Light and buttery. Just your normal croissant.
    Morning Bun
    -- Fluffy and sweet with a citrus flavour. A bit of a messy eat because of the sugar topping but still pretty good.
    Brioche Bread Pudding (with Raspberries and Blackberries)
    -- Very wet/juicy. Would have preferred it to be a little less so, but it was still enjoyable. I liked the berries but would have preferred strawberries.
    Tres Leches Cake: Sweet coconut milk moistened chiffon, layered with cajeta and crema
    -- Probably my favourite sweet out of our choices. Light and creamy.
    Banana Cream Tart (4"): Flaky pastry coated in dark chocolate with caramel, pastry cream, and lightly sweetened cream
    -- I thought this would be my favourite, except I'm not a fan of dark chocolate. And there was a bit too much of it for me. But the rest of it was good.
    Croque Monsieur: Open face sandwich with bechamel, gruyere, thyme and pepper. Topped with smoked Niman Ranch ham.
    -- Pretty good. Pretty much exactly what you expect it to be. Comes with a pickled carrot which is nice.

    Overall the food was pretty good but not worth all the hype. I wouldn't wait in a long line for it, so I'm glad our line was decently short and moved quickly. But I'm definitely glad I got to try this place out and we had an enjoyable meal.
